        "richtext_RexrVk": {
          "type": "richtext",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text_content": "<h2>Why Should You Wear a Lifting Belt?</h2><p>A weightlifting belt is a trendy accessory for every powerlifter, bodybuilder, and occasional gym-goer. It's an <a href=\"https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1080/10803548.1995.11076326\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1080/10803548.1995.11076326\">important lifting gear that will protect your body when dealing with extreme weights</a>. These belts are designed to stabilize the spine by increasing intra-abdominal pressure.</p><p><a href=\"https://blog.warmbody-coldmind.com/guides/nylon-vs-leather-lifting-belt/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://blog.warmbody-coldmind.com/guides/nylon-vs-leather-lifting-belt/\">Lifting belts</a> provide better support and stability to the lower back and abdominal muscles during tough training with heavy weights. They are typically worn around the waist and tightened with a lever located on the front or side of the belt. Let's outline the key point on how it works.</p><p>When performing compound movements, such as deadlifts, squats, and overhead presses, your core muscles experience great tension as they keep you from bending or flexing under extreme weights.</p><p>By the way, core muscles include the diaphragm on the front, obliques on your sides, and the spinal erectors on your back, as well as your transverse abdominis, which are deep core muscles believed to be the body’s internal weight-lifting belt. The additional core-bracing support not only mitigates stress on the vertebrae and intervertebral discs but also keeps the optimal posture during heavy lifts.</p><p>Maintaining a neutral spine is integral in lifting techniques, which is exactly what a lifting belt helps you achieve. It serves a purpose in a particular occasion: working with heavy weight and lifting even heavier weights while protecting your spine. The <a href=\"https://journals.lww.com/spinejournal/abstract/2000/06150/effects_of_a_lifting_belt_on_spine_moments_and.18.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://journals.lww.com/spinejournal/abstract/2000/06150/effects_of_a_lifting_belt_on_spine_moments_and.18.aspx\">research indicates that the belt reduces</a> the forward bending of the spine during the symmetric loads.</p><p>Additionally, it reduces the forward flexion moment acting on the spine and restricted lateral bending as well. Another key point is the breathing technique: when powerlifters lift heavy loads, they take a breath into their abdomen by engaging core muscles. They hold the breath throughout the rep, exhaling at the top of the movement.</p><p>It causes intra-abdominal pressure, so their trunk stays stiff when working with heavy weights. The lever weightlifting belt will support your abdomen and back to mitigate occasional strains and trauma.</p>",
            "rich_text_image_alt": "",
            "half_width_main_image": false
          }
        },
        "video_fBdTJd": {
          "type": "video",
          "settings": {
            "youtube_video_url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U-S-Tb7KNb4"
